  "prompt": "Is it true that everyone has to have chickenpox at least once in their lifetime?",
  "response": "No, it is not true that everyone has to have chickenpox at least once in their lifetime. While chickenpox, caused by the varicella-zoster virus, was once considered a common childhood disease, vaccination has significantly reduced the number of cases. The varicella vaccine, which is part of routine childhood immunizations in many countries, effectively protects against chickenpox. Many people can now go through life without ever contracting the disease, thanks to widespread vaccination efforts. Additionally, some people may have immunity due to exposure to the virus without showing symptoms, or they might have received the vaccine.",
